129
00:12:43,563 --> 00:12:59,493
Paper 26097 offered by Vice President Lazaro, whereas first responders and veterans are disproportionately affected by mental health disorders including PTSD, anxiety and depression and whereas many first responders and veterans can feel uncomfortable reaching out for help with mental health concerns.

130
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:08,582
due to negative stigma, often instead turning to substances and whereas people with substance use disorder also face significant negative stigma in this community and elsewhere.

131
00:13:08,722 --> 00:13:19,364
Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford City Council discuss and promote the important work of Medford's recovery coach, Chris Summa, who is now offering a regular weekly recovery meeting for first responders and veterans dealing with substance use disorder.

132
00:13:19,825 --> 00:13:23,365
This meeting takes place at the First Baptist Church of Medford every Tuesday at 7 p.m.

133
00:13:23,845 --> 00:13:30,167
Be it further resolved that the city council invite Chris and Director of Veterans Services, Victoria Shaw, to the May 26th meeting to discuss and promote the recovery group.

134
00:13:30,695 --> 00:13:31,636
Vice President Lazaro.

135
00:13:33,617 --> 00:13:34,397
Thank you very much.

136
00:13:35,978 --> 00:13:41,701
I would invite the two leaders of this group who have worked really hard to put this together.

137
00:13:41,721 --> 00:13:47,164
This is a group that meets.

138
00:13:47,224 --> 00:13:50,906
It's open to anybody who would like to partake of the services.

139
00:13:52,007 --> 00:13:55,208
Chris Summa has been here at city council meetings a few times before.

140
00:13:57,257 --> 00:13:59,960
I appreciate any opportunity to have him come back.

141
00:14:01,462 --> 00:14:06,067
Director Shah has been also present for a number of occasions.

142
00:14:06,368 --> 00:14:09,452
I understand your speech at the Memorial Day celebration.

143
00:14:09,472 --> 00:14:09,992
I couldn't make it.

144
00:14:10,012 --> 00:14:10,373
I'm sorry.

145
00:14:10,393 --> 00:14:13,797
It was very lovely and happy to have you here again.

146
00:14:16,551 --> 00:14:24,696
The, so recovery groups are like an unaffiliated kind of AA meeting, but you don't have to do anything specific.

147
00:14:24,736 --> 00:14:29,759
It's just talking about your place in recovery where you're at.

148
00:14:30,540 --> 00:14:41,907
And Chris put together this group specifically for people who are veterans or first responders and in that, having that in common with each other.

149
00:14:43,291 --> 00:14:46,696
can allow people to feel more comfortable sharing about their experiences.

150
00:14:46,816 --> 00:14:56,328
So rather than me speaking for you, I just wanted to give you an opportunity to come and tell us and the public about this group and give you an opportunity to

151
00:14:58,401 --> 00:15:01,663
sort of talk more about it and let people know how they can join.

152
00:15:01,823 --> 00:15:09,208
Also, incidentally, just today I received my email and I saw that it was on Facebook, too, that the mayor's office put out a press release, which is really cool.

153
00:15:09,769 --> 00:15:12,311
And so it's on, you know, a lot of different channels.

154
00:15:12,391 --> 00:15:15,032
So, you know, I hope you're not overrun tonight.

155
00:15:15,273 --> 00:15:16,634
I mean, you're not there, unfortunately.

156
00:15:16,834 --> 00:15:18,155
I'm sorry we ran an hour over.

157
00:15:18,175 --> 00:15:18,975
You probably could have been.

158
00:15:20,236 --> 00:15:21,517
So thank you for coming.

159
00:15:22,117 --> 00:15:27,441
Please, I would love through the chair to invite you to speak about the group and how it's been going.

160
00:15:28,902 --> 00:15:30,604
Thanks, Chris and Veronica.

161
00:15:30,864 --> 00:15:31,665
Sorry, go ahead.

162
00:15:31,705 --> 00:15:38,813
So I'm going to just kind of give you a little bit of background on how we got to here, and then I'll turn it over to Chris to give you all of the details.

163
00:15:39,374 --> 00:15:46,122
So the group actually came about because you'll know that one of my biggest passions is working on homeless veterans.

164
00:15:47,590 --> 00:15:59,421
And doing my research, discovered that one of the biggest causes for veterans to become homeless is substance abuse and other disorders, substance disorders.

165
00:15:59,441 --> 00:16:05,806
And the push within the veterans community is how do we deal with there?

166
00:16:05,846 --> 00:16:07,368
Do we deal with the substance abuse first?

167
00:16:07,388 --> 00:16:10,410
Do we deal with the homelessness first?

168
00:16:10,430 --> 00:16:12,292
And there's really no good solution.

169
00:16:14,906 --> 00:16:17,327
For me, I want to do both.

170
00:16:17,927 --> 00:16:23,708
So I've already spoken with you guys about the initiatives I'm doing to help end veteran homelessness here in Medford.

171
00:16:24,208 --> 00:16:28,269
But then we have to address the issues of substance abuse.

172
00:16:28,769 --> 00:16:32,490
How do we prevent veterans from needing the other services?

173
00:16:32,830 --> 00:16:34,711
We have to address it at the root cause.

174
00:16:35,711 --> 00:16:37,211
And that's where Chris comes in.

175
00:16:37,351 --> 00:16:40,612
I approached him, said, hey, let's team up.

176
00:16:40,772 --> 00:16:43,533
So many of our first responders are veterans.

177
00:16:43,573 --> 00:16:44,673
They go hand in hand.

178
00:16:45,774 --> 00:17:00,684
Let's create a group here in Medford for anybody, any veteran, any first responder from any city, they need some place to just go and talk with their brothers and sisters about whatever is bothering them, just getting through the day.

179
00:17:01,865 --> 00:17:04,446
From my own personal experience working with the VA,

180
00:17:05,267 --> 00:17:13,352
There's a lot of groups, but when you come in and you're not an older veteran or male, there's really not much out there.

181
00:17:14,413 --> 00:17:22,198
It was very uncomfortable for me to sit in groups with men who were twice my age, didn't have my same experiences.

182
00:17:22,278 --> 00:17:26,161
They had their own amazing service experiences, but they weren't the same.

183
00:17:26,221 --> 00:17:27,522
They're different generations.

184
00:17:28,222 --> 00:17:30,364
And I wanted to create something here

185
00:17:31,783 --> 00:17:36,924
for my generation of veteran, for the younger generation of veterans.

186
00:17:37,984 --> 00:17:40,925
That's how Chris comes in, because he's the expert.

187
00:17:40,965 --> 00:17:46,886
So I'll let him tell you how we formed the group, what's going to happen, and everything else.

188
00:17:48,726 --> 00:17:49,106
Thank you.

189
00:17:49,506 --> 00:17:50,266
I appreciate that.

190
00:17:51,786 --> 00:17:53,347
So just a little back story on me.

191
00:17:53,527 --> 00:17:58,728
Before I got into recovery work, I worked in law enforcement for a little over 10 years.

192
00:18:01,008 --> 00:18:09,893
I found that I was unable to talk about the issues that we face on a regular basis, and there wasn't a safe outlet for that.

193
00:18:10,613 --> 00:18:15,155
And getting into recovery work, first responders were always near and dear to my heart.

194
00:18:15,676 --> 00:18:17,477
As soon as I met Veronica, it was like,

195
00:18:18,471 --> 00:18:19,452
the perfect storm.

196
00:18:19,692 --> 00:18:22,213
We came together and it just made sense.

197
00:18:23,614 --> 00:18:31,558
I personally went through McLean Hospital, the detox program, and they have a program there called the LEADER program, which is designed for first responders.

198
00:18:32,118 --> 00:18:39,962
And there was a meeting that they had in Belmont, and they used to call it a badge meeting, and it was first responders, veterans.

199
00:18:40,322 --> 00:18:42,543
And it was the only time that I really felt at home.

200
00:18:43,143 --> 00:18:44,064
When I got out of there,

201
00:18:44,704 --> 00:18:48,907
Getting to Belmont was an issue, especially early in recovery.

202
00:18:49,387 --> 00:18:53,049
You take travel time, you take people that may not have vehicles, transportation.

203
00:18:53,650 --> 00:18:54,450
It's tough to get there.

204
00:18:54,470 --> 00:18:57,292
You're looking three, four hours to get back and forth for a meeting.

205
00:18:57,572 --> 00:18:59,593
And in early recovery, it's difficult.

206
00:19:01,479 --> 00:19:06,642
When we started talking about this, as you guys know, I run the recovery group, which is an all recovery group on Wednesdays.

207
00:19:06,722 --> 00:19:07,543
Anybody can attend.

208
00:19:08,043 --> 00:19:13,727
And we said it would be great if we had something close by, something that's T accessible, something that everybody can get to.

209
00:19:13,747 --> 00:19:15,788
It doesn't matter what your zip code is.

210
00:19:16,148 --> 00:19:16,688
You're welcome.

211
00:19:17,449 --> 00:19:22,672
And it's for all former and current military veterans, first responders.

212
00:19:23,733 --> 00:19:26,775
And it's titled a recovery group.

213
00:19:27,395 --> 00:19:34,000
But realistically, it's a safe place where people can come and dump whatever they're holding inside on the table.

214
00:19:34,600 --> 00:19:39,423
And maybe in those moments, you wouldn't burn your life to the ground like I did.

215
00:19:39,803 --> 00:19:42,525
If I had an outlet like that, maybe things would have been different.

216
00:19:42,906 --> 00:19:49,570
Because the stuff that we see, even other groups that I attend, I can't talk about with other people.

217
00:19:50,010 --> 00:19:51,591
I'm gonna use the phrase civilians.

218
00:19:52,172 --> 00:19:56,375
But I can't talk about it with civilians because we're put in situations where we see

219
00:19:57,615 --> 00:19:58,476
intense things.

220
00:19:58,556 --> 00:20:00,256
We do intense things.

221
00:20:00,777 --> 00:20:04,199
Things that regular people may look at and shake their heads at.

222
00:20:04,819 --> 00:20:15,485
At the group that we run, when I say something that has to do with my past or experiences that I've had, when I look around the room, everybody's nodding their head yes.

223
00:20:15,845 --> 00:20:17,466
They understand where I'm coming from.

224
00:20:17,886 --> 00:20:21,268
So yes, we do offer support for substance use disorder.

225
00:20:22,329 --> 00:20:24,250
But we offer support for anybody that

226
00:20:25,219 --> 00:20:30,981
has served, is serving, that can benefit from a safe place to talk all of your problems out.

227
00:20:31,061 --> 00:20:37,163
It doesn't matter if it's PTSD, it doesn't matter if it's alcohol, it doesn't matter if it's drugs, it makes no difference.

228
00:20:37,663 --> 00:20:38,883
It's just having an outlet.

229
00:20:39,423 --> 00:20:47,506
And I just wanna say, we've actually, we've started it the beginning of this month, and we have a good core group of people.

230
00:20:48,966 --> 00:20:53,448
Thank you so much for letting us come and present, because getting the word out is,

231
00:20:54,608 --> 00:20:55,888
Everything right now.

232
00:20:55,928 --> 00:21:13,593
What's running based on where the mouth but with the press release and everything that's happening really excited to see where it can take us this is it's just great for for anybody that can benefit from this and As you all know like substance use disorder and mental health disorder it touches all of us and sometimes

233
00:21:14,859 --> 00:21:20,021
people think that because you're wearing a uniform, because you're serving, it doesn't affect you.

234
00:21:20,421 --> 00:21:22,082
It does, because we're people first.

235
00:21:22,642 --> 00:21:26,944
The jobs that we do and the positions that we hold, they don't give us extra strength.

236
00:21:27,484 --> 00:21:33,706
We're supposed to have extra strength, and that's what's drilled into us, but it doesn't mean that you can't talk about things.

237
00:21:33,746 --> 00:21:35,947
It doesn't mean that we don't bleed just like everybody else.

238
00:21:36,487 --> 00:21:39,788
So this is just a safe outlet for people to come, talk, get support.

239
00:21:40,509 --> 00:21:40,889
The group,

240
00:21:41,844 --> 00:21:51,029
is running a supportive nature in terms of, you know, if you bring something up and somebody else has, you know, a similar situation in the group, we offer advice, we offer support.

241
00:21:51,329 --> 00:22:04,476
So just to give you a quick example, this past meeting that we just had this past week, the topic of conversation, because I'll generally say, you know, does anybody have anything pressing that they wanna discuss tonight?

242
00:22:04,936 --> 00:22:08,518
And the topic that was discussed this past week was reaching out for help.

243
00:22:09,218 --> 00:22:11,840
So it wasn't even related to substances.

244
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:14,382
It was just the difficulty in reaching out for help.

245
00:22:14,783 --> 00:22:21,308
The difficulty in being the person that everybody turns to for help, and now you're the one having to ask for help.

246
00:22:21,828 --> 00:22:32,157
And everybody in the group just offered what they do to reach out for help, and it's very supportive, it's very loving, it's very nurturing, and it's just, most importantly, it's a safe space.

247
00:22:32,617 --> 00:22:38,222
And the group, as you said, it's every Tuesday night, 7 p.m., First Baptist Church on Oakland Street.

248
00:22:39,463 --> 00:22:44,266
And yeah, we're looking forward to, you know, getting this going and getting as many people involved as possible.

249
00:22:44,306 --> 00:22:48,049
