1002
01:13:52,258 --> 01:13:54,120
Good evening, President Villescaz and City Councilors.

1003
01:13:54,620 --> 01:14:02,967
I am here tonight to respectfully request and recommend that your Honorable Body adopt the City of Medford's Hazard Mitigation Plan 2025 update.

1004
01:14:05,828 --> 01:14:12,911
I know I sent it to you all and it is a lengthy plan and I do appreciate your time reviewing it.

1005
01:14:12,931 --> 01:14:20,034
The process was long, over a year and a half, but I believe the plan is really informative.

1006
01:14:20,394 --> 01:14:25,356
I think it's laid out in an easy to read format and it is very comprehensive.

1007
01:14:27,072 --> 01:14:32,235
So the hazard mitigation plan is basically required by the Federal Disaster Mitigation Act of 2000.

1008
01:14:34,036 --> 01:14:41,501
It's a five-year roadmap for reducing impacts of hazards like floods, storms, and extreme weather.

1009
01:14:41,521 --> 01:14:52,648
It highlights protections and projects and actions that the city can take ahead of time to reduce risks to human life and injury, as well as infrastructure.

1010
01:14:52,668 --> 01:14:55,669
And it's basically there to help

1011
01:14:57,852 --> 01:15:00,474
minimize loss and damage from natural disasters.

1012
01:15:01,195 --> 01:15:08,960
We are required to do this by FEMA in order to receive federal funding going forward for any mitigation projects.

1013
01:15:09,801 --> 01:15:16,686
The good news is once this is approved and adopted, we do not have to revisit it again until 2030.

1014
01:15:19,331 --> 01:15:25,753
The approval of funding, so this is an update to the 2017 plan, which you're like, well, that's not five years.

1015
01:15:26,914 --> 01:15:34,596
The little thing called COVID happened in between, but also we did actually receive approval for funding to move forward with this in 2022.

1016
01:15:35,737 --> 01:15:41,178
We just did not actually receive the funding until close to 2024.

1017
01:15:41,338 --> 01:15:44,440
So that's why it's been such a delay as well.

1018
01:15:45,040 --> 01:15:48,621
But a big part of this whole plan was really community engagement.

1019
01:15:49,870 --> 01:16:09,381
We went out there, we did surveys, we did community meetings, we had what we called conversation groups, and those were basically with community-based organizations like the Senior Center, the Walnut Street Center, West Medford Community Center, the Family Network folks.

1020
01:16:10,321 --> 01:16:12,062
So we did a lot of outreach.

1021
01:16:12,102 --> 01:16:16,705
We did also several community meetings where we gathered input as well.

1022
01:16:17,245 --> 01:16:25,987
And I think if you look at the end of the plan, it's a lot of information about what folks were concerned about and what their comments were and what we tried to address.

1023
01:16:26,087 --> 01:16:31,648
So I really am proud of the community engagement that we did.

1024
01:16:31,668 --> 01:16:45,530
Really what the residents did emphasize was the need for financial supports, including home improvements to prepare for hazards, reliable emergency communications, especially for people with limited English literacy,

1025
01:16:46,350 --> 01:16:57,102
stronger neighborhood support systems for seniors, caregivers, and people with chronic health conditions, and better coordination between city and trusted community-based organizations.

1026
01:16:58,467 --> 01:17:02,070
So we took all of that into consideration as we were doing the plan.

1027
01:17:02,971 --> 01:17:06,393
So FEMA is pretty prescriptive as to what we have to include in the plan.

1028
01:17:07,334 --> 01:17:17,982
But some of what we did as far as our natural hazards include flooding events, storm events, extreme temperature, geological hazards.

1029
01:17:20,118 --> 01:17:29,907
And, you know, the geological hazards probably are the lowest risks because they include like brush fire, brush fires, droughts, earthquakes and landslides.

1030
01:17:30,868 --> 01:17:38,975
But, you know, the most common for us would be droughts, of course, because it streams out water supplies, but our highest risks are really the flooding events.

1031
01:17:39,876 --> 01:17:45,663
We've had several of those over the past years, and storm events are moderate to risk as well.

1032
01:17:46,404 --> 01:17:52,210
So like winter storms with disrupt power, and you know Northeasterners and, and that kind of thing.

1033
01:17:53,042 --> 01:18:02,224
We don't see tornadoes typically here but we have known in the past few years they have kind of come about in local areas.

1034
01:18:04,065 --> 01:18:10,046
So I think you know I certainly don't want to go through the 200 page plan.

1035
01:18:10,226 --> 01:18:16,288
But if you have questions, I guess I just would point that the real need of the plan is probably around

1036
01:18:17,125 --> 01:18:22,671
page 167 with our new updated hazard mitigation goals.

1037
01:18:23,351 --> 01:18:30,839
And also, you know, in there as well as the status of our previous mitigation goals from our 2017 plan.

1038
01:18:31,620 --> 01:18:33,061
And most of those were actually met.

1039
01:18:33,361 --> 01:18:39,047
And if they weren't met, they were deprioritized because they were no longer deemed as

1040
01:18:40,268 --> 01:18:42,470
being, you know, important or necessary.

1041
01:18:43,311 --> 01:18:58,125
So I'm proud to say that most of that was done, but we did find kind of a gap in the way those 2017 mitigation goals were put forth, like they were more done like limited and departmental areas or silos.

1042
01:18:58,786 --> 01:19:04,632
And so what we're proposing going forward with this plan is to really kind of bring in a group or a team

1043
01:19:05,380 --> 01:19:17,634
of community mitigation, hazard mitigation folks, and to really work on this going forward as a team, and making sure that we're not just operating in silos.

1044
01:19:17,734 --> 01:19:20,997
So I think that's important.

1045
01:19:22,278 --> 01:19:27,160
But yeah, I'm happy to take any questions or any more thoughts.

1046
01:19:27,660 --> 01:19:38,704
I think you will find the response to some of the public comment period towards the end of the plan, at the very end of the plan, is very interesting and informative.

1047
01:19:39,344 --> 01:19:41,105
So I invite you to look at that.

1048
01:19:42,605 --> 01:19:45,946
But certainly, you know, get to answer any questions.

1049
01:19:46,326 --> 01:19:47,947
And thank you.

1050
